      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "At a molecular level, the Maillard reaction creates hundreds of different flavor compounds—such as melanoidins and aldehydes—as proteins and sugars break down. These new molecules are responsible for the complex, aromatic notes like toasted or nutty, rather than just a visual change. Essentially, the reaction generates the volatile, flavorful compounds that we perceive as \"good crust flavor.\"",
      "source": "target",
